      "id": "d3ad4c9c32f981ca",
      "text": "If, on the other hand, one starts from autopoiesis, it becomes easier to understand that the structuring of one's consciousness, one's memory, and one's preferences is the result of an individual system history that has something to do, not least, with the cultural offer to actualize conformity or deviation. If it were only about transmission and everything else had to be described as a defect, it would not be possible to explain how individuality comes about, because then there would only be a variety of copies, depending on the range of cultural differentiation."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a25ee0971b602da5",
      "text": "But if one gives every individual, every consciousness undergoing socialization, the chance to accept or to deviate, either to say yes or no or to think and to seek individuality in deviation, one probably arrives at a much better theory of the genesis of personal idiosyncrasies from the history of tactical adaptation, of enforced deviation, of concealed deviation, of the recognition of norms that one cannot quite accept, or even of the internalization of norms that one more or less affirms inwardly at first only because of coercion, but later because of the need for consistency with one's own behavior. These different [[Path]]s, which are open to an individual and compatible with autopoiesis, provide a better [[Starting Point]] for a theory of socialization than the transmission model."
